Author-Name:   Folkes, Valerie S
Author-Name:  Patrick, Vanessa M
Title: 
 The Positivity Effect in Perceptions of Services: Seen One, Seen Them All?

Journal: Journal of Consumer Research
Pages: 125-37
Issue: 1
Volume: 30
Year: 2003
Month:  June 
Abstract:

 A series of studies show converging evidence of a positivity effect in
 consumers' inferences about service providers. When the consumer has
 little experience with a service, positive information about a single
 employee leads to inferences that the firm's other service providers are
 similarly positive to a greater extent than negative information leads to
 inferences that the firm's other service providers are similarly negative.
 Four studies were conducted that varied in the amount of information about
 the service provider, the firm, and the service. The positivity effect was
 supported despite differences across studies in methods as well as
 measures.


